Package semsim.model.collection

Class SemSimModel

java.lang.Object
semsim.SemSimObject
semsim.model.collection.SemSimCollection
semsim.model.collection.SemSimModel
All Implemented Interfaces:
Annotatable
public class SemSimModel
extends SemSimCollection
implements Annotatable
A SemSim model is a declarative representation of a quantified physical system. SemSim models represent both the computational and physical aspects of a model. In other words, they capture not only the model's mathematics, but also what the mathematics represent, physically.

At the most fundamental level, SemSim models are comprised of DataStructures, which represent the numerical values of physical properties (concentrations, pressures, etc.). These physical properties are properties of either physical entities or physical processes.

For example, a model of cellular glycolysis may represent the chemical concentration of intracellular glucose with a variable called "cgluc." This can be captured within a SemSim model by creating a DataStructure with the name "cgluc" and a corresponding PhysicalPropertyInComposite that is annotated against the Ontology of Physics for Biology term "Chemical concentration." This PhysicalPropertyInComposite would be a property of a PhysicalEntity representing intracellular glucose. In this case we would use a CompositePhysicalEntity that consists of a singular PhysicalEntity representing glucose that is linked to another singular PhysicalEntity representing the cytosol via the "part of" SemSimRelations.SemSimRelation. To capture the biological meaning of this physical entity in a machine-readable way, we could annotate the singular physical entities against CHEBI:glucose and FMA:cytosol.

This is an example of a "composite annotation," which are explained in more detail in

Gennari et al. Multiple ontologies in action: Managing composite annotations. Journal of Biomedical Informatics, 2011. 44(1):146-154.

SemSim model DataStructures can also be linked to the mathematical code in the model that solves them and their physical units (e.g. kg, molar, mmHg - see UnitOfMeasurement). DataStructures can also be grouped within SemSim models to form Submodels. These groupings are intended to facilitate model extraction tasks. Submodels may represent a biological or computational model aspect.
